54/* This file contains three techniques for performing Dead Store
55 Elimination (dse).
56
57 * The first technique performs dse locally on any base address. It
58 is based on the cselib which is a local value numbering technique.
59 This technique is local to a basic block but deals with a fairly
60 general addresses.
61
62 * The second technique performs dse globally but is restricted to
63 base addresses that are either constant or are relative to the
64 frame_pointer.
65
66 * The third technique, (which is only done after register allocation)
67 processes the spill slots. This differs from the second
68 technique because it takes advantage of the fact that spilling is
69 completely free from the effects of aliasing.
70
71 Logically, dse is a backwards dataflow problem. A store can be
72 deleted if it if cannot be reached in the backward direction by any
73 use of the value being stored. However, the local technique uses a
74 forwards scan of the basic block because cselib requires that the
75 block be processed in that order.
76
77 The pass is logically broken into 7 steps:
78
79 0) Initialization.
80
81 1) The local algorithm, as well as scanning the insns for the two
82 global algorithms.
83
84 2) Analysis to see if the global algs are necessary. In the case
85 of stores base on a constant address, there must be at least two
86 stores to that address, to make it possible to delete some of the
87 stores. In the case of stores off of the frame or spill related
88 stores, only one store to an address is necessary because those
89 stores die at the end of the function.
90
91 3) Set up the global dataflow equations based on processing the
92 info parsed in the first step.
93
94 4) Solve the dataflow equations.
95
96 5) Delete the insns that the global analysis has indicated are
97 unnecessary.
98
99 6) Delete insns that store the same value as preceding store
100 where the earlier store couldn't be eliminated.
101
102 7) Cleanup.
103
104 This step uses cselib and canon_rtx to build the largest expression
105 possible for each address. This pass is a forwards pass through
106 each basic block. From the point of view of the global technique,
107 the first pass could examine a block in either direction. The
108 forwards ordering is to accommodate cselib.
109
110 We make a simplifying assumption: addresses fall into four broad
111 categories:
112
113 1) base has rtx_varies_p == false, offset is constant.
114 2) base has rtx_varies_p == false, offset variable.
115 3) base has rtx_varies_p == true, offset constant.
116 4) base has rtx_varies_p == true, offset variable.
117
118 The local passes are able to process all 4 kinds of addresses. The
119 global pass only handles 1).
120
121 The global problem is formulated as follows:
122
123 A store, S1, to address A, where A is not relative to the stack
124 frame, can be eliminated if all paths from S1 to the end of the
125 function contain another store to A before a read to A.
126
127 If the address A is relative to the stack frame, a store S2 to A
128 can be eliminated if there are no paths from S2 that reach the
129 end of the function that read A before another store to A. In
130 this case S2 can be deleted if there are paths from S2 to the
131 end of the function that have no reads or writes to A. This
132 second case allows stores to the stack frame to be deleted that
133 would otherwise die when the function returns. This cannot be
134 done if stores_off_frame_dead_at_return is not true. See the doc
135 for that variable for when this variable is false.
136
137 The global problem is formulated as a backwards set union
138 dataflow problem where the stores are the gens and reads are the
139 kills. Set union problems are rare and require some special
140 handling given our representation of bitmaps. A straightforward
141 implementation requires a lot of bitmaps filled with 1s.
142 These are expensive and cumbersome in our bitmap formulation so
143 care has been taken to avoid large vectors filled with 1s. See
144 the comments in bb_info and in the dataflow confluence functions
145 for details.
146
147 There are two places for further enhancements to this algorithm:
148
149 1) The original dse which was embedded in a pass called flow also
150 did local address forwarding. For example in
151
152 A <- r100
153 ... <- A
154
155 flow would replace the right hand side of the second insn with a
156 reference to r100. Most of the information is available to add this
157 to this pass. It has not done it because it is a lot of work in
158 the case that either r100 is assigned to between the first and
159 second insn and/or the second insn is a load of part of the value
160 stored by the first insn.
161
162 insn 5 in gcc.c-torture/compile/990203-1.c simple case.
163 insn 15 in gcc.c-torture/execute/20001017-2.c simple case.
164 insn 25 in gcc.c-torture/execute/20001026-1.c simple case.
165 insn 44 in gcc.c-torture/execute/20010910-1.c simple case.
166
167 2) The cleaning up of spill code is quite profitable. It currently
168 depends on reading tea leaves and chicken entrails left by reload.
169 This pass depends on reload creating a singleton alias set for each
170 spill slot and telling the next dse pass which of these alias sets
171 are the singletons. Rather than analyze the addresses of the
172 spills, dse's spill processing just does analysis of the loads and
173 stores that use those alias sets. There are three cases where this
174 falls short:
175
176 a) Reload sometimes creates the slot for one mode of access, and
177 then inserts loads and/or stores for a smaller mode. In this
178 case, the current code just punts on the slot. The proper thing
179 to do is to back out and use one bit vector position for each
180 byte of the entity associated with the slot. This depends on
181 KNOWING that reload always generates the accesses for each of the
182 bytes in some canonical (read that easy to understand several
183 passes after reload happens) way.
184
185 b) Reload sometimes decides that spill slot it allocated was not
186 large enough for the mode and goes back and allocates more slots
187 with the same mode and alias set. The backout in this case is a
188 little more graceful than (a). In this case the slot is unmarked
189 as being a spill slot and if final address comes out to be based
190 off the frame pointer, the global algorithm handles this slot.
191
192 c) For any pass that may prespill, there is currently no
193 mechanism to tell the dse pass that the slot being used has the
194 special properties that reload uses. It may be that all that is
195 required is to have those passes make the same calls that reload
196 does, assuming that the alias sets can be manipulated in the same
197 way. */
198

222/* This structure holds information about a candidate store. */
223struct store_info
224{
225
226 /* False means this is a clobber. */
227 bool is_set;
228
229 /* False if a single HOST_WIDE_INT bitmap is used for positions_needed. */
230 bool is_large;
231
232 /* The id of the mem group of the base address. If rtx_varies_p is
233 true, this is -1. Otherwise, it is the index into the group
234 table. */
235 int group_id;
236
237 /* This is the cselib value. */
238 cselib_val *cse_base;
239
240 /* This canonized mem. */
241 rtx mem;
242
243 /* Canonized MEM address for use by canon_true_dependence. */
244 rtx mem_addr;
245
246 /* The offset of the first and byte before the last byte associated
247 with the operation. */
248 HOST_WIDE_INT begin, end;
249
250 union
251 {
252 /* A bitmask as wide as the number of bytes in the word that
253 contains a 1 if the byte may be needed. The store is unused if
254 all of the bits are 0. This is used if IS_LARGE is false. */
255 unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT small_bitmask;
256
257 struct
258 {
259 /* A bitmap with one bit per byte. Cleared bit means the position
260 is needed. Used if IS_LARGE is false. */
261 bitmap bmap;
262
263 /* Number of set bits (i.e. unneeded bytes) in BITMAP. If it is
264 equal to END - BEGIN, the whole store is unused. */
265 int count;
266 } large;
267 } positions_needed;
268
269 /* The next store info for this insn. */
270 struct store_info *next;
271
272 /* The right hand side of the store. This is used if there is a
273 subsequent reload of the mems address somewhere later in the
274 basic block. */
275 rtx rhs;
276
277 /* If rhs is or holds a constant, this contains that constant,
278 otherwise NULL. */
279 rtx const_rhs;
280
281 /* Set if this store stores the same constant value as REDUNDANT_REASON
282 insn stored. These aren't eliminated early, because doing that
283 might prevent the earlier larger store to be eliminated. */
284 struct insn_info_type *redundant_reason;
285};

287/* Return a bitmask with the first N low bits set. */
288
289static unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT
290lowpart_bitmask (int n)
291{
292 unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT mask = HOST_WIDE_INT_M1U;
293#ifdef __NetBSD__ // XXXMRG
294 gcc_assert(n >= 0 && n <= HOST_BITS_PER_WIDE_INT);
295 if (n == 0)
296 return 0;
297#endif
298 return mask >> (HOST_BITS_PER_WIDE_INT - n);
299}

327/* One of these records is created for each insn. */
328
329struct insn_info_type
330{
331 /* Set true if the insn contains a store but the insn itself cannot
332 be deleted. This is set if the insn is a parallel and there is
333 more than one non dead output or if the insn is in some way
334 volatile. */
335 bool cannot_delete;
336
337 /* This field is only used by the global algorithm. It is set true
338 if the insn contains any read of mem except for a (1). This is
339 also set if the insn is a call or has a clobber mem. If the insn
340 contains a wild read, the use_rec will be null. */
341 bool wild_read;
342
343 /* This is true only for CALL instructions which could potentially read
344 any non-frame memory location. This field is used by the global
345 algorithm. */
346 bool non_frame_wild_read;
347
348 /* This field is only used for the processing of const functions.
349 These functions cannot read memory, but they can read the stack
350 because that is where they may get their parms. We need to be
351 this conservative because, like the store motion pass, we don't
352 consider CALL_INSN_FUNCTION_USAGE when processing call insns.
353 Moreover, we need to distinguish two cases:
354 1. Before reload (register elimination), the stores related to
355 outgoing arguments are stack pointer based and thus deemed
356 of non-constant base in this pass. This requires special
357 handling but also means that the frame pointer based stores
358 need not be killed upon encountering a const function call.
359 2. After reload, the stores related to outgoing arguments can be
360 either stack pointer or hard frame pointer based. This means
361 that we have no other choice than also killing all the frame
362 pointer based stores upon encountering a const function call.
363 This field is set after reload for const function calls and before
364 reload for const tail function calls on targets where arg pointer
365 is the frame pointer. Having this set is less severe than a wild
366 read, it just means that all the frame related stores are killed
367 rather than all the stores. */
368 bool frame_read;
369
370 /* This field is only used for the processing of const functions.
371 It is set if the insn may contain a stack pointer based store. */
372 bool stack_pointer_based;
373
374 /* This is true if any of the sets within the store contains a
375 cselib base. Such stores can only be deleted by the local
376 algorithm. */
377 bool contains_cselib_groups;
378
379 /* The insn. */
380 rtx_insn *insn;
381
382 /* The list of mem sets or mem clobbers that are contained in this
383 insn. If the insn is deletable, it contains only one mem set.
384 But it could also contain clobbers. Insns that contain more than
385 one mem set are not deletable, but each of those mems are here in
386 order to provide info to delete other insns. */
387 store_info *store_rec;
388
389 /* The linked list of mem uses in this insn. Only the reads from
390 rtx bases are listed here. The reads to cselib bases are
391 completely processed during the first scan and so are never
392 created. */
393 read_info_t read_rec;
394
395 /* The live fixed registers. We assume only fixed registers can
396 cause trouble by being clobbered from an expanded pattern;
397 storing only the live fixed registers (rather than all registers)
398 means less memory needs to be allocated / copied for the individual
399 stores. */
400 regset fixed_regs_live;
401
402 /* The prev insn in the basic block. */
403 struct insn_info_type * prev_insn;
404
405 /* The linked list of insns that are in consideration for removal in
406 the forwards pass through the basic block. This pointer may be
407 trash as it is not cleared when a wild read occurs. The only
408 time it is guaranteed to be correct is when the traversal starts
409 at active_local_stores. */
410 struct insn_info_type * next_local_store;
411};
412typedef struct insn_info_type *insn_info_t;

414static object_allocator<insn_info_type> insn_info_type_pool ("insn_info_pool");

416/* The linked list of stores that are under consideration in this
417 basic block. */
418static insn_info_t active_local_stores;
419static int active_local_stores_len;

421struct dse_bb_info_type
422{
423 /* Pointer to the insn info for the last insn in the block. These
424 are linked so this is how all of the insns are reached. During
425 scanning this is the current insn being scanned. */
426 insn_info_t last_insn;
427
428 /* The info for the global dataflow problem. */
429
430
431 /* This is set if the transfer function should and in the wild_read
432 bitmap before applying the kill and gen sets. That vector knocks
433 out most of the bits in the bitmap and thus speeds up the
434 operations. */
435 bool apply_wild_read;
436
437 /* The following 4 bitvectors hold information about which positions
438 of which stores are live or dead. They are indexed by
439 get_bitmap_index. */
440
441 /* The set of store positions that exist in this block before a wild read. */
442 bitmap gen;
443
444 /* The set of load positions that exist in this block above the
445 same position of a store. */
446 bitmap kill;
447
448 /* The set of stores that reach the top of the block without being
449 killed by a read.
450
451 Do not represent the in if it is all ones. Note that this is
452 what the bitvector should logically be initialized to for a set
453 intersection problem. However, like the kill set, this is too
454 expensive. So initially, the in set will only be created for the
455 exit block and any block that contains a wild read. */
456 bitmap in;
457
458 /* The set of stores that reach the bottom of the block from it's
459 successors.
460
461 Do not represent the in if it is all ones. Note that this is
462 what the bitvector should logically be initialized to for a set
463 intersection problem. However, like the kill and in set, this is
464 too expensive. So what is done is that the confluence operator
465 just initializes the vector from one of the out sets of the
466 successors of the block. */
467 bitmap out;
468
469 /* The following bitvector is indexed by the reg number. It
470 contains the set of regs that are live at the current instruction
471 being processed. While it contains info for all of the
472 registers, only the hard registers are actually examined. It is used
473 to assure that shift and/or add sequences that are inserted do not
474 accidentally clobber live hard regs. */
475 bitmap regs_live;
476};

486/* There is a group_info for each rtx base that is used to reference
487 memory. There are also not many of the rtx bases because they are
488 very limited in scope. */
489
490struct group_info
491{
492 /* The actual base of the address. */
493 rtx rtx_base;
494
495 /* The sequential id of the base. This allows us to have a
496 canonical ordering of these that is not based on addresses. */
497 int id;
498
499 /* True if there are any positions that are to be processed
500 globally. */
501 bool process_globally;
502
503 /* True if the base of this group is either the frame_pointer or
504 hard_frame_pointer. */
505 bool frame_related;
506
507 /* A mem wrapped around the base pointer for the group in order to do
508 read dependency. It must be given BLKmode in order to encompass all
509 the possible offsets from the base. */
510 rtx base_mem;
511
512 /* Canonized version of base_mem's address. */
513 rtx canon_base_addr;
514
515 /* These two sets of two bitmaps are used to keep track of how many
516 stores are actually referencing that position from this base. We
517 only do this for rtx bases as this will be used to assign
518 positions in the bitmaps for the global problem. Bit N is set in
519 store1 on the first store for offset N. Bit N is set in store2
520 for the second store to offset N. This is all we need since we
521 only care about offsets that have two or more stores for them.
522
523 The "_n" suffix is for offsets less than 0 and the "_p" suffix is
524 for 0 and greater offsets.
525
526 There is one special case here, for stores into the stack frame,
527 we will or store1 into store2 before deciding which stores look
528 at globally. This is because stores to the stack frame that have
529 no other reads before the end of the function can also be
530 deleted. */
531 bitmap store1_n, store1_p, store2_n, store2_p;
532
533 /* These bitmaps keep track of offsets in this group escape this function.
534 An offset escapes if it corresponds to a named variable whose
535 addressable flag is set. */
536 bitmap escaped_n, escaped_p;
537
538 /* The positions in this bitmap have the same assignments as the in,
539 out, gen and kill bitmaps. This bitmap is all zeros except for
540 the positions that are occupied by stores for this group. */
541 bitmap group_kill;
542
543 /* The offset_map is used to map the offsets from this base into
544 positions in the global bitmaps. It is only created after all of
545 the all of stores have been scanned and we know which ones we
546 care about. */
547 int *offset_map_n, *offset_map_p;
548 int offset_map_size_n, offset_map_size_p;
549};

602/* Hashtable callbacks for maintaining the "bases" field of
603 store_group_info, given that the addresses are function invariants. */

605struct invariant_group_base_hasher : nofree_ptr_hash <group_info>
606{
607 static inline hashval_t hash (const group_info *);
608 static inline bool equal (const group_info *, const group_info *);
609};
610
611inline bool
612invariant_group_base_hasher::equal (const group_info *gi1,
613 const group_info *gi2)
614{
615 return rtx_equal_p (gi1->rtx_base, gi2->rtx_base);
616}
617
618inline hashval_t
619invariant_group_base_hasher::hash (const group_info *gi)
620{
621 int do_not_record;
622 return hash_rtx (gi->rtx_base, Pmode, &do_not_record, NULL, false);
623}

629/* Get the GROUP for BASE. Add a new group if it is not there. */
630
631static group_info *
632get_group_info (rtx base)
633{
634 struct group_info tmp_gi;
635 group_info *gi;
636 group_info **slot;
637
638 gcc_assert (base != NULL_RTX);
639
640 /* Find the store_base_info structure for BASE, creating a new one
641 if necessary. */
642 tmp_gi.rtx_base = base;
643 slot = rtx_group_table->find_slot (&tmp_gi, INSERT);
644 gi = *slot;
645
646 if (gi == NULL)
647 {
648 *slot = gi = group_info_pool.allocate ();
649 gi->rtx_base = base;
650 gi->id = rtx_group_next_id++;
651 gi->base_mem = gen_rtx_MEM (BLKmode, base);
652 gi->canon_base_addr = canon_rtx (base);
653 gi->store1_n = BITMAP_ALLOC (&dse_bitmap_obstack);
654 gi->store1_p = BITMAP_ALLOC (&dse_bitmap_obstack);
655 gi->store2_n = BITMAP_ALLOC (&dse_bitmap_obstack);
656 gi->store2_p = BITMAP_ALLOC (&dse_bitmap_obstack);
657 gi->escaped_p = BITMAP_ALLOC (&dse_bitmap_obstack);
658 gi->escaped_n = BITMAP_ALLOC (&dse_bitmap_obstack);
659 gi->group_kill = BITMAP_ALLOC (&dse_bitmap_obstack);
660 gi->process_globally = false;
661 gi->frame_related =
662 (base == frame_pointer_rtx) || (base == hard_frame_pointer_rtx);
663 gi->offset_map_size_n = 0;
664 gi->offset_map_size_p = 0;
665 gi->offset_map_n = NULL;
666 gi->offset_map_p = NULL;
667 rtx_group_vec.safe_push (gi);
668 }
669
670 return gi;
671}

696 init_alias_analysis ();
697}

701/*----------------------------------------------------------------------------
702 First step.
703
704 Scan all of the insns. Any random ordering of the blocks is fine.
705 Each block is scanned in forward order to accommodate cselib which
706 is used to remove stores with non-constant bases.
707----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
708
709/* Delete all of the store_info recs from INSN_INFO. */
710
711static void
712free_store_info (insn_info_t insn_info)
713{
714 store_info *cur = insn_info->store_rec;
715 while (cur)
716 {
717 store_info *next = cur->next;
718 if (cur->is_large)
719 BITMAP_FREE (cur->positions_needed.large.bmap);
720 if (cur->cse_base)
721 cse_store_info_pool.remove (cur);
722 else
723 rtx_store_info_pool.remove (cur);
724 cur = next;
725 }
726
727 insn_info->cannot_delete = true;
728 insn_info->contains_cselib_groups = false;
729 insn_info->store_rec = NULL;
730}
731
732struct note_add_store_info
733{
734 rtx_insn *first, *current;
735 regset fixed_regs_live;
736 bool failure;
737};
738
739/* Callback for emit_inc_dec_insn_before via note_stores.
740 Check if a register is clobbered which is live afterwards. */
741
742static void
743note_add_store (rtx loc, const_rtx expr ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED, void *data)
744{
745 rtx_insn *insn;
746 note_add_store_info *info = (note_add_store_info *) data;
747
748 if (!REG_P (loc))
749 return;
750
751 /* If this register is referenced by the current or an earlier insn,
752 that's OK. E.g. this applies to the register that is being incremented
753 with this addition. */
754 for (insn = info->first;
755 insn != NEXT_INSN (info->current);
756 insn = NEXT_INSN (insn))
757 if (reg_referenced_p (loc, PATTERN (insn)))
758 return;
759
760 /* If we come here, we have a clobber of a register that's only OK
761 if that register is not live. If we don't have liveness information
762 available, fail now. */
763 if (!info->fixed_regs_live)
764 {
765 info->failure = true;
766 return;
767 }
768 /* Now check if this is a live fixed register. */
769 unsigned int end_regno = END_REGNO (loc);
770 for (unsigned int regno = REGNO (loc); regno < end_regno; ++regno)
771 if (REGNO_REG_SET_P (info->fixed_regs_live, regno))
772 info->failure = true;
773}
774
775/* Callback for for_each_inc_dec that emits an INSN that sets DEST to
776 SRC + SRCOFF before insn ARG. */
777
778static int
779emit_inc_dec_insn_before (rtx mem ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED,
780 rtx op ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED,
781 rtx dest, rtx src, rtx srcoff, void *arg)
782{
783 insn_info_t insn_info = (insn_info_t) arg;
784 rtx_insn *insn = insn_info->insn, *new_insn, *cur;
785 note_add_store_info info;
786
787 /* We can reuse all operands without copying, because we are about
788 to delete the insn that contained it. */
789 if (srcoff)
790 {
791 start_sequence ();
792 emit_insn (gen_add3_insn (dest, src, srcoff));
793 new_insn = get_insns ();
794 end_sequence ();
795 }
796 else
797 new_insn = gen_move_insn (dest, src);
798 info.first = new_insn;
799 info.fixed_regs_live = insn_info->fixed_regs_live;
800 info.failure = false;
801 for (cur = new_insn; cur; cur = NEXT_INSN (cur))
802 {
803 info.current = cur;
804 note_stores (PATTERN (cur), note_add_store, &info);
805 }
806
807 /* If a failure was flagged above, return 1 so that for_each_inc_dec will
808 return it immediately, communicating the failure to its caller. */
809 if (info.failure)
810 return 1;
811
812 emit_insn_before (new_insn, insn);
813
814 return 0;
815}
816
817/* Before we delete INSN_INFO->INSN, make sure that the auto inc/dec, if it
818 is there, is split into a separate insn.
819 Return true on success (or if there was nothing to do), false on failure. */
820
821static bool
822check_for_inc_dec_1 (insn_info_t insn_info)
823{
824 rtx_insn *insn = insn_info->insn;
825 rtx note = find_reg_note (insn, REG_INC, NULL_RTX);
826 if (note)
827 return for_each_inc_dec (PATTERN (insn), emit_inc_dec_insn_before,
828 insn_info) == 0;
829 return true;
830}

833/* Entry point for postreload. If you work on reload_cse, or you need this
834 anywhere else, consider if you can provide register liveness information
835 and add a parameter to this function so that it can be passed down in
836 insn_info.fixed_regs_live. */
837bool
838check_for_inc_dec (rtx_insn *insn)
839{
840 insn_info_type insn_info;
841 rtx note;
842
843 insn_info.insn = insn;
844 insn_info.fixed_regs_live = NULL;
845 note = find_reg_note (insn, REG_INC, NULL_RTX);
846 if (note)
847 return for_each_inc_dec (PATTERN (insn), emit_inc_dec_insn_before,
848 &insn_info) == 0;
849 return true;
850}

852/* Delete the insn and free all of the fields inside INSN_INFO. */
853
854static void
855delete_dead_store_insn (insn_info_t insn_info)
856{
857 read_info_t read_info;
858
859 if (!dbg_cnt (dse))
860 return;
861
862 if (!check_for_inc_dec_1 (insn_info))
863 return;
864 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
865 fprintf (dump_file, "Locally deleting insn %d\n",
866 INSN_UID (insn_info->insn));
867
868 free_store_info (insn_info);
869 read_info = insn_info->read_rec;

881 insn_info->insn = NULL;
882
883 insn_info->wild_read = false;
884}

886/* Return whether DECL, a local variable, can possibly escape the current
887 function scope. */
888
889static bool
890local_variable_can_escape (tree decl)
891{
892 if (TREE_ADDRESSABLE (decl))
893 return true;
894
895 /* If this is a partitioned variable, we need to consider all the variables
896 in the partition. This is necessary because a store into one of them can
897 be replaced with a store into another and this may not change the outcome
898 of the escape analysis. */
899 if (cfun->gimple_df->decls_to_pointers != NULL)
900 {
901 tree *namep = cfun->gimple_df->decls_to_pointers->get (decl);
902 if (namep)
903 return TREE_ADDRESSABLE (*namep);
904 }
905
906 return false;
907}
908
909/* Return whether EXPR can possibly escape the current function scope. */
910
911static bool
912can_escape (tree expr)
913{
914 tree base;
915 if (!expr)
916 return true;
917 base = get_base_address (expr);
918 if (DECL_P (base)
919 && !may_be_aliased (base)
920 && !(VAR_P (base)
921 && !DECL_EXTERNAL (base)
922 && !TREE_STATIC (base)
923 && local_variable_can_escape (base)))
924 return false;
925 return true;
926}

928/* Set the store* bitmaps offset_map_size* fields in GROUP based on
929 OFFSET and WIDTH. */
930
931static void
932set_usage_bits (group_info *group, HOST_WIDE_INT offset, HOST_WIDE_INT width,
933 tree expr)
934{
935 HOST_WIDE_INT i;
936 bool expr_escapes = can_escape (expr);
937 if (offset > -MAX_OFFSET && offset + width < MAX_OFFSET)
938 for (i=offset; i<offset+width; i++)
939 {
940 bitmap store1;
941 bitmap store2;
942 bitmap escaped;
943 int ai;
944 if (i < 0)
945 {
946 store1 = group->store1_n;
947 store2 = group->store2_n;
948 escaped = group->escaped_n;
949 ai = -i;
950 }
951 else
952 {
953 store1 = group->store1_p;
954 store2 = group->store2_p;
955 escaped = group->escaped_p;
956 ai = i;
957 }
958
959 if (!bitmap_set_bit (store1, ai))
960 bitmap_set_bit (store2, ai);
961 else
962 {
963 if (i < 0)
964 {
965 if (group->offset_map_size_n < ai)
966 group->offset_map_size_n = ai;
967 }
968 else
969 {
970 if (group->offset_map_size_p < ai)
971 group->offset_map_size_p = ai;
972 }
973 }
974 if (expr_escapes)
975 bitmap_set_bit (escaped, ai);
976 }
977}

1024/* Return true if X is a constant or one of the registers that behave
1025 as a constant over the life of a function. This is equivalent to
1026 !rtx_varies_p for memory addresses. */
1027
1028static bool
1029const_or_frame_p (rtx x)
1030{
1031 if (CONSTANT_P (x))
1032 return true;
1033
1034 if (GET_CODE (x) == REG)
1035 {
1036 /* Note that we have to test for the actual rtx used for the frame
1037 and arg pointers and not just the register number in case we have
1038 eliminated the frame and/or arg pointer and are using it
1039 for pseudos. */
1040 if (x == frame_pointer_rtx || x == hard_frame_pointer_rtx
1041 /* The arg pointer varies if it is not a fixed register. */
1042 || (x == arg_pointer_rtx && fixed_regs[ARG_POINTER_REGNUM])
1043 || x == pic_offset_table_rtx)
1044 return true;
1045 return false;
1046 }
1047
1048 return false;
1049}
1050
1051/* Take all reasonable action to put the address of MEM into the form
1052 that we can do analysis on.
1053
1054 The gold standard is to get the address into the form: address +
1055 OFFSET where address is something that rtx_varies_p considers a
1056 constant. When we can get the address in this form, we can do
1057 global analysis on it. Note that for constant bases, address is
1058 not actually returned, only the group_id. The address can be
1059 obtained from that.
1060
1061 If that fails, we try cselib to get a value we can at least use
1062 locally. If that fails we return false.
1063
1064 The GROUP_ID is set to -1 for cselib bases and the index of the
1065 group for non_varying bases.
1066
1067 FOR_READ is true if this is a mem read and false if not. */
1068
1069static bool
1070canon_address (rtx mem,
1071 int *group_id,
1072 HOST_WIDE_INT *offset,
1073 cselib_val **base)
1074{
1075 machine_mode address_mode = get_address_mode (mem);
1076 rtx mem_address = XEXP (mem, 0);
1077 rtx expanded_address, address;
1078 int expanded;
1079
1080 cselib_lookup (mem_address, address_mode, 1, GET_MODE (mem));
1081
1082 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1083 {
1084 fprintf (dump_file, " mem: ");
1085 print_inline_rtx (dump_file, mem_address, 0);
1086 fprintf (dump_file, "\n");
1087 }
1088
1089 /* First see if just canon_rtx (mem_address) is const or frame,
1090 if not, try cselib_expand_value_rtx and call canon_rtx on that. */
1091 address = NULL_RTX;
1092 for (expanded = 0; expanded < 2; expanded++)
1093 {
1094 if (expanded)
1095 {
1096 /* Use cselib to replace all of the reg references with the full
1097 expression. This will take care of the case where we have
1098
1099 r_x = base + offset;
1100 val = *r_x;
1101
1102 by making it into
1103
1104 val = *(base + offset); */
1105
1106 expanded_address = cselib_expand_value_rtx (mem_address,
1107 scratch, 5);
1108
1109 /* If this fails, just go with the address from first
1110 iteration. */
1111 if (!expanded_address)
1112 break;
1113 }
1114 else
1115 expanded_address = mem_address;
1116
1117 /* Split the address into canonical BASE + OFFSET terms. */
1118 address = canon_rtx (expanded_address);
1119
1120 *offset = 0;
1121
1122 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1123 {
1124 if (expanded)
1125 {
1126 fprintf (dump_file, "\n after cselib_expand address: ");
1127 print_inline_rtx (dump_file, expanded_address, 0);
1128 fprintf (dump_file, "\n");
1129 }
1130
1131 fprintf (dump_file, "\n after canon_rtx address: ");
1132 print_inline_rtx (dump_file, address, 0);
1133 fprintf (dump_file, "\n");
1134 }
1135
1136 if (GET_CODE (address) == CONST)
1137 address = XEXP (address, 0);
1138
1139 if (GET_CODE (address) == PLUS
1140 && CONST_INT_P (XEXP (address, 1)))
1141 {
1142 *offset = INTVAL (XEXP (address, 1));
1143 address = XEXP (address, 0);
1144 }
1145
1146 if (ADDR_SPACE_GENERIC_P (MEM_ADDR_SPACE (mem))
1147 && const_or_frame_p (address))
1148 {
1149 group_info *group = get_group_info (address);
1150
1151 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1152 fprintf (dump_file, " gid=%d offset=%d \n",
1153 group->id, (int)*offset);
1154 *base = NULL;
1155 *group_id = group->id;
1156 return true;
1157 }
1158 }
1159
1160 *base = cselib_lookup (address, address_mode, true, GET_MODE (mem));
1161 *group_id = -1;
1162
1163 if (*base == NULL)
1164 {
1165 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1166 fprintf (dump_file, " no cselib val - should be a wild read.\n");
1167 return false;
1168 }
1169 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1170 fprintf (dump_file, " varying cselib base=%u:%u offset = %d\n",
1171 (*base)->uid, (*base)->hash, (int)*offset);
1172 return true;
1173}

1177
1178static void
1179clear_rhs_from_active_local_stores (void)
1180{

1198/* Mark byte POS bytes from the beginning of store S_INFO as unneeded. */
1199
1200static inline void
1201set_position_unneeded (store_info *s_info, int pos)
1202{
1203 if (__builtin_expect (s_info->is_large, false))
1204 {
1205 if (bitmap_set_bit (s_info->positions_needed.large.bmap, pos))
1206 s_info->positions_needed.large.count++;
1207 }
1208 else
1209 s_info->positions_needed.small_bitmask
1210 &= ~(HOST_WIDE_INT_1U << pos);
1211}
1212
1213/* Mark the whole store S_INFO as unneeded. */
1214
1215static inline void
1216set_all_positions_unneeded (store_info *s_info)
1217{
1218 if (__builtin_expect (s_info->is_large, false))
1219 {
1220 int pos, end = s_info->end - s_info->begin;
1221 for (pos = 0; pos < end; pos++)
1222 bitmap_set_bit (s_info->positions_needed.large.bmap, pos);
1223 s_info->positions_needed.large.count = end;
1224 }
1225 else
1226 s_info->positions_needed.small_bitmask = HOST_WIDE_INT_0U;
1227}
1228
1229/* Return TRUE if any bytes from S_INFO store are needed. */
1230
1231static inline bool
1232any_positions_needed_p (store_info *s_info)
1233{
1234 if (__builtin_expect (s_info->is_large, false))
1235 return (s_info->positions_needed.large.count
1236 < s_info->end - s_info->begin);
1237 else
1238 return (s_info->positions_needed.small_bitmask != HOST_WIDE_INT_0U);
1239}
1240
1241/* Return TRUE if all bytes START through START+WIDTH-1 from S_INFO
1242 store are needed. */
1243
1244static inline bool
1245all_positions_needed_p (store_info *s_info, int start, int width)
1246{
1247 if (__builtin_expect (s_info->is_large, false))
1248 {
1249 int end = start + width;
1250 while (start < end)
1251 if (bitmap_bit_p (s_info->positions_needed.large.bmap, start++))
1252 return false;
1253 return true;
1254 }
1255 else
1256 {
1257 unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT mask = lowpart_bitmask (width) << start;
1258 return (s_info->positions_needed.small_bitmask & mask) == mask;
1259 }
1260}

1266
1267/* BODY is an instruction pattern that belongs to INSN. Return 1 if
1268 there is a candidate store, after adding it to the appropriate
1269 local store group if so. */
1270
1271static int
1272record_store (rtx body, bb_info_t bb_info)
1273{
1274 rtx mem, rhs, const_rhs, mem_addr;
1275 HOST_WIDE_INT offset = 0;
1276 HOST_WIDE_INT width = 0;
1277 insn_info_t insn_info = bb_info->last_insn;
1278 store_info *store_info = NULL;
1279 int group_id;
1280 cselib_val *base = NULL;
1281 insn_info_t ptr, last, redundant_reason;
1282 bool store_is_unused;
1283
1284 if (GET_CODE (body) != SET && GET_CODE (body) != CLOBBER)
1285 return 0;
1286
1287 mem = SET_DEST (body);
1288
1289 /* If this is not used, then this cannot be used to keep the insn
1290 from being deleted. On the other hand, it does provide something
1291 that can be used to prove that another store is dead. */
1292 store_is_unused
1293 = (find_reg_note (insn_info->insn, REG_UNUSED, mem) != NULL);
1294
1295 /* Check whether that value is a suitable memory location. */
1296 if (!MEM_P (mem))
1297 {
1298 /* If the set or clobber is unused, then it does not effect our
1299 ability to get rid of the entire insn. */
1300 if (!store_is_unused)
1301 insn_info->cannot_delete = true;
1302 return 0;
1303 }
1304
1305 /* At this point we know mem is a mem. */
1306 if (GET_MODE (mem) == BLKmode)
1307 {
1308 if (GET_CODE (XEXP (mem, 0)) == SCRATCH)
1309 {
1310 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1311 fprintf (dump_file, " adding wild read for (clobber (mem:BLK (scratch))\n");
1312 add_wild_read (bb_info);
1313 insn_info->cannot_delete = true;
1314 return 0;
1315 }
1316 /* Handle (set (mem:BLK (addr) [... S36 ...]) (const_int 0))
1317 as memset (addr, 0, 36); */
1318 else if (!MEM_SIZE_KNOWN_P (mem)
1319 || MEM_SIZE (mem) <= 0
1320 || MEM_SIZE (mem) > MAX_OFFSET
1321 || GET_CODE (body) != SET
1322 || !CONST_INT_P (SET_SRC (body)))
1323 {
1324 if (!store_is_unused)
1325 {
1326 /* If the set or clobber is unused, then it does not effect our
1327 ability to get rid of the entire insn. */
1328 insn_info->cannot_delete = true;
1329 clear_rhs_from_active_local_stores ();
1330 }
1331 return 0;
1332 }
1333 }
1334
1335 /* We can still process a volatile mem, we just cannot delete it. */
1336 if (MEM_VOLATILE_P (mem))
1337 insn_info->cannot_delete = true;
1338
1339 if (!canon_address (mem, &group_id, &offset, &base))
1340 {
1341 clear_rhs_from_active_local_stores ();
1342 return 0;
1343 }
1344
1345 if (GET_MODE (mem) == BLKmode)
1346 width = MEM_SIZE (mem);
1347 else
1348 width = GET_MODE_SIZE (GET_MODE (mem));
1349
1350 if (width == 0)
1351 return 0;
1352
1353 if (group_id >= 0)
1354 {
1355 /* In the restrictive case where the base is a constant or the
1356 frame pointer we can do global analysis. */
1357
1358 group_info *group
1359 = rtx_group_vec[group_id];
1360 tree expr = MEM_EXPR (mem);
1361
1362 store_info = rtx_store_info_pool.allocate ();
1363 set_usage_bits (group, offset, width, expr);
1364
1365 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1366 fprintf (dump_file, " processing const base store gid=%d[%d..%d)\n",
1367 group_id, (int)offset, (int)(offset+width));
1368 }
1369 else
1370 {
1371 if (may_be_sp_based_p (XEXP (mem, 0)))
1372 insn_info->stack_pointer_based = true;
1373 insn_info->contains_cselib_groups = true;
1374
1375 store_info = cse_store_info_pool.allocate ();
1376 group_id = -1;
1377
1378 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1379 fprintf (dump_file, " processing cselib store [%d..%d)\n",
1380 (int)offset, (int)(offset+width));
1381 }
1382
1383 const_rhs = rhs = NULL_RTX;
1384 if (GET_CODE (body) == SET
1385 /* No place to keep the value after ra. */
1386 && !reload_completed
1387 && (REG_P (SET_SRC (body))
1388 || GET_CODE (SET_SRC (body)) == SUBREG
1389 || CONSTANT_P (SET_SRC (body)))
1390 && !MEM_VOLATILE_P (mem)
1391 /* Sometimes the store and reload is used for truncation and
1392 rounding. */
1393 && !(FLOAT_MODE_P (GET_MODE (mem)) && (flag_float_store)))
1394 {
1395 rhs = SET_SRC (body);
1396 if (CONSTANT_P (rhs))
1397 const_rhs = rhs;
1398 else if (body == PATTERN (insn_info->insn))
1399 {
1400 rtx tem = find_reg_note (insn_info->insn, REG_EQUAL, NULL_RTX);
1401 if (tem && CONSTANT_P (XEXP (tem, 0)))
1402 const_rhs = XEXP (tem, 0);
1403 }
1404 if (const_rhs == NULL_RTX && REG_P (rhs))
1405 {
1406 rtx tem = cselib_expand_value_rtx (rhs, scratch, 5);
1407
1408 if (tem && CONSTANT_P (tem))
1409 const_rhs = tem;
1410 }
1411 }
1412
1413 /* Check to see if this stores causes some other stores to be
1414 dead. */
1415 ptr = active_local_stores;
1416 last = NULL;
1417 redundant_reason = NULL;
1418 mem = canon_rtx (mem);
1419
1420 if (group_id < 0)
1421 mem_addr = base->val_rtx;
1422 else
1423 {
1424 group_info *group = rtx_group_vec[group_id];
1425 mem_addr = group->canon_base_addr;
1426 }
1427 if (offset)
1428 mem_addr = plus_constant (get_address_mode (mem), mem_addr, offset);
1429
1430 while (ptr)
1431 {
1432 insn_info_t next = ptr->next_local_store;
1433 struct store_info *s_info = ptr->store_rec;
1434 bool del = true;
1435
1436 /* Skip the clobbers. We delete the active insn if this insn
1437 shadows the set. To have been put on the active list, it
1438 has exactly on set. */
1439 while (!s_info->is_set)
1440 s_info = s_info->next;
1441
1442 if (s_info->group_id == group_id && s_info->cse_base == base)
1443 {
1444 HOST_WIDE_INT i;
1445 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1446 fprintf (dump_file, " trying store in insn=%d gid=%d[%d..%d)\n",
1447 INSN_UID (ptr->insn), s_info->group_id,
1448 (int)s_info->begin, (int)s_info->end);
1449
1450 /* Even if PTR won't be eliminated as unneeded, if both
1451 PTR and this insn store the same constant value, we might
1452 eliminate this insn instead. */
1453 if (s_info->const_rhs
1454 && const_rhs
1455 && offset >= s_info->begin
1456 && offset + width <= s_info->end
1457 && all_positions_needed_p (s_info, offset - s_info->begin,
1458 width)
1459 /* We can only remove the later store if the earlier aliases
1460 at least all accesses the later one. */
1461 && (MEM_ALIAS_SET (mem) == MEM_ALIAS_SET (s_info->mem)
1462 || alias_set_subset_of (MEM_ALIAS_SET (mem),
1463 MEM_ALIAS_SET (s_info->mem))))
1464 {
1465 if (GET_MODE (mem) == BLKmode)
1466 {
1467 if (GET_MODE (s_info->mem) == BLKmode
1468 && s_info->const_rhs == const_rhs)
1469 redundant_reason = ptr;
1470 }
1471 else if (s_info->const_rhs == const0_rtx
1472 && const_rhs == const0_rtx)
1473 redundant_reason = ptr;
1474 else
1475 {
1476 rtx val;
1477 start_sequence ();
1478 val = get_stored_val (s_info, GET_MODE (mem),
1479 offset, offset + width,
1480 BLOCK_FOR_INSN (insn_info->insn),
1481 true);
1482 if (get_insns () != NULL)
1483 val = NULL_RTX;
1484 end_sequence ();
1485 if (val && rtx_equal_p (val, const_rhs))
1486 redundant_reason = ptr;
1487 }
1488 }
1489
1490 for (i = MAX (offset, s_info->begin);
1491 i < offset + width && i < s_info->end;
1492 i++)
1493 set_position_unneeded (s_info, i - s_info->begin);
1494 }
1495 else if (s_info->rhs)
1496 /* Need to see if it is possible for this store to overwrite
1497 the value of store_info. If it is, set the rhs to NULL to
1498 keep it from being used to remove a load. */
1499 {
1500 if (canon_output_dependence (s_info->mem, true,
1501 mem, GET_MODE (mem),
1502 mem_addr))
1503 {
1504 s_info->rhs = NULL;
1505 s_info->const_rhs = NULL;
1506 }
1507 }
1508
1509 /* An insn can be deleted if every position of every one of
1510 its s_infos is zero. */
1511 if (any_positions_needed_p (s_info))
1512 del = false;
1513
1514 if (del)
1515 {
1516 insn_info_t insn_to_delete = ptr;
1517
1518 active_local_stores_len--;
1519 if (last)
1520 last->next_local_store = ptr->next_local_store;
1521 else
1522 active_local_stores = ptr->next_local_store;
1523
1524 if (!insn_to_delete->cannot_delete)
1525 delete_dead_store_insn (insn_to_delete);
1526 }
1527 else
1528 last = ptr;
1529
1530 ptr = next;
1531 }
1532
1533 /* Finish filling in the store_info. */
1534 store_info->next = insn_info->store_rec;
1535 insn_info->store_rec = store_info;
1536 store_info->mem = mem;
1537 store_info->mem_addr = mem_addr;
1538 store_info->cse_base = base;
1539 if (width > HOST_BITS_PER_WIDE_INT)
1540 {
1541 store_info->is_large = true;
1542 store_info->positions_needed.large.count = 0;
1543 store_info->positions_needed.large.bmap = BITMAP_ALLOC (&dse_bitmap_obstack);
1544 }
1545 else
1546 {
1547 store_info->is_large = false;
1548 store_info->positions_needed.small_bitmask = lowpart_bitmask (width);
1549 }
1550 store_info->group_id = group_id;
1551 store_info->begin = offset;
1552 store_info->end = offset + width;
1553 store_info->is_set = GET_CODE (body) == SET;
1554 store_info->rhs = rhs;
1555 store_info->const_rhs = const_rhs;
1556 store_info->redundant_reason = redundant_reason;
1557
1558 /* If this is a clobber, we return 0. We will only be able to
1559 delete this insn if there is only one store USED store, but we
1560 can use the clobber to delete other stores earlier. */
1561 return store_info->is_set ? 1 : 0;
1562}

1565static void
1566dump_insn_info (const char * start, insn_info_t insn_info)
1567{
1568 fprintf (dump_file, "%s insn=%d %s\n", start,
1569 INSN_UID (insn_info->insn),
1570 insn_info->store_rec ? "has store" : "naked");
1571}

1573
1574/* If the modes are different and the value's source and target do not
1575 line up, we need to extract the value from lower part of the rhs of
1576 the store, shift it, and then put it into a form that can be shoved
1577 into the read_insn. This function generates a right SHIFT of a
1578 value that is at least ACCESS_SIZE bytes wide of READ_MODE. The
1579 shift sequence is returned or NULL if we failed to find a
1580 shift. */
1581
1582static rtx
1583find_shift_sequence (int access_size,
1584 store_info *store_info,
1585 machine_mode read_mode,
1586 int shift, bool speed, bool require_cst)
1587{
1588 machine_mode store_mode = GET_MODE (store_info->mem);
1589 machine_mode new_mode;
1590 rtx read_reg = NULL;
1591
1592 /* Some machines like the x86 have shift insns for each size of
1593 operand. Other machines like the ppc or the ia-64 may only have
1594 shift insns that shift values within 32 or 64 bit registers.
1595 This loop tries to find the smallest shift insn that will right
1596 justify the value we want to read but is available in one insn on
1597 the machine. */
1598
1599 for (new_mode = smallest_mode_for_size (access_size * BITS_PER_UNIT,
1600 MODE_INT);
1601 GET_MODE_BITSIZE (new_mode) <= BITS_PER_WORD;
1602 new_mode = GET_MODE_WIDER_MODE (new_mode))
1603 {
1604 rtx target, new_reg, new_lhs;
1605 rtx_insn *shift_seq, *insn;
1606 int cost;
1607
1608 /* If a constant was stored into memory, try to simplify it here,
1609 otherwise the cost of the shift might preclude this optimization
1610 e.g. at -Os, even when no actual shift will be needed. */
1611 if (store_info->const_rhs)
1612 {
1613 unsigned int byte = subreg_lowpart_offset (new_mode, store_mode);
1614 rtx ret = simplify_subreg (new_mode, store_info->const_rhs,
1615 store_mode, byte);
1616 if (ret && CONSTANT_P (ret))
1617 {
1618 ret = simplify_const_binary_operation (LSHIFTRT, new_mode,
1619 ret, GEN_INT (shift));
1620 if (ret && CONSTANT_P (ret))
1621 {
1622 byte = subreg_lowpart_offset (read_mode, new_mode);
1623 ret = simplify_subreg (read_mode, ret, new_mode, byte);
1624 if (ret && CONSTANT_P (ret)
1625 && (set_src_cost (ret, read_mode, speed)
1626 <= COSTS_N_INSNS (1)))
1627 return ret;
1628 }
1629 }
1630 }
1631
1632 if (require_cst)
1633 return NULL_RTX;
1634
1635 /* Try a wider mode if truncating the store mode to NEW_MODE
1636 requires a real instruction. */
1637 if (GET_MODE_BITSIZE (new_mode) < GET_MODE_BITSIZE (store_mode)
1638 && !TRULY_NOOP_TRUNCATION_MODES_P (new_mode, store_mode))
1639 continue;
1640
1641 /* Also try a wider mode if the necessary punning is either not
1642 desirable or not possible. */
1643 if (!CONSTANT_P (store_info->rhs)
1644 && !MODES_TIEABLE_P (new_mode, store_mode))
1645 continue;
1646
1647 new_reg = gen_reg_rtx (new_mode);
1648
1649 start_sequence ();
1650
1651 /* In theory we could also check for an ashr. Ian Taylor knows
1652 of one dsp where the cost of these two was not the same. But
1653 this really is a rare case anyway. */
1654 target = expand_binop (new_mode, lshr_optab, new_reg,
1655 GEN_INT (shift), new_reg, 1, OPTAB_DIRECT);
1656
1657 shift_seq = get_insns ();
1658 end_sequence ();
1659
1660 if (target != new_reg || shift_seq == NULL)
1661 continue;
1662
1663 cost = 0;
1664 for (insn = shift_seq; insn != NULL_RTX; insn = NEXT_INSN (insn))
1665 if (INSN_P (insn))
1666 cost += insn_rtx_cost (PATTERN (insn), speed);
1667
1668 /* The computation up to here is essentially independent
1669 of the arguments and could be precomputed. It may
1670 not be worth doing so. We could precompute if
1671 worthwhile or at least cache the results. The result
1672 technically depends on both SHIFT and ACCESS_SIZE,
1673 but in practice the answer will depend only on ACCESS_SIZE. */
1674
1675 if (cost > COSTS_N_INSNS (1))
1676 continue;
1677
1678 new_lhs = extract_low_bits (new_mode, store_mode,
1679 copy_rtx (store_info->rhs));
1680 if (new_lhs == NULL_RTX)
1681 continue;
1682
1683 /* We found an acceptable shift. Generate a move to
1684 take the value from the store and put it into the
1685 shift pseudo, then shift it, then generate another
1686 move to put in into the target of the read. */
1687 emit_move_insn (new_reg, new_lhs);
1688 emit_insn (shift_seq);
1689 read_reg = extract_low_bits (read_mode, new_mode, new_reg);
1690 break;
1691 }
1692
1693 return read_reg;
1694}

1697/* Call back for note_stores to find the hard regs set or clobbered by
1698 insn. Data is a bitmap of the hardregs set so far. */
1699
1700static void
1701look_for_hardregs (rtx x, const_rtx pat ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED, void *data)
1702{
1703 bitmap regs_set = (bitmap) data;
1704
1705 if (REG_P (x)
1706 && HARD_REGISTER_P (x))
1707 bitmap_set_range (regs_set, REGNO (x), REG_NREGS (x));
1708}
1709
1710/* Helper function for replace_read and record_store.
1711 Attempt to return a value stored in STORE_INFO, from READ_BEGIN
1712 to one before READ_END bytes read in READ_MODE. Return NULL
1713 if not successful. If REQUIRE_CST is true, return always constant. */
1714
1715static rtx
1716get_stored_val (store_info *store_info, machine_mode read_mode,
1717 HOST_WIDE_INT read_begin, HOST_WIDE_INT read_end,
1718 basic_block bb, bool require_cst)
1719{
1720 machine_mode store_mode = GET_MODE (store_info->mem);
1721 int shift;
1722 int access_size; /* In bytes. */
1723 rtx read_reg;
1724
1725 /* To get here the read is within the boundaries of the write so
1726 shift will never be negative. Start out with the shift being in
1727 bytes. */
1728 if (store_mode == BLKmode)
1729 shift = 0;
1730 else if (BYTES_BIG_ENDIAN)
1731 shift = store_info->end - read_end;
1732 else
1733 shift = read_begin - store_info->begin;
1734
1735 access_size = shift + GET_MODE_SIZE (read_mode);
1736
1737 /* From now on it is bits. */
1738 shift *= BITS_PER_UNIT;
1739
1740 if (shift)
1741 read_reg = find_shift_sequence (access_size, store_info, read_mode, shift,
1742 optimize_bb_for_speed_p (bb),
1743 require_cst);
1744 else if (store_mode == BLKmode)
1745 {
1746 /* The store is a memset (addr, const_val, const_size). */
1747 gcc_assert (CONST_INT_P (store_info->rhs));
1748 store_mode = int_mode_for_mode (read_mode);
1749 if (store_mode == BLKmode)
1750 read_reg = NULL_RTX;
1751 else if (store_info->rhs == const0_rtx)
1752 read_reg = extract_low_bits (read_mode, store_mode, const0_rtx);
1753 else if (GET_MODE_BITSIZE (store_mode) > HOST_BITS_PER_WIDE_INT
1754 || BITS_PER_UNIT >= HOST_BITS_PER_WIDE_INT)
1755 read_reg = NULL_RTX;
1756 else
1757 {
1758 unsigned HOST_WIDE_INT c
1759 = INTVAL (store_info->rhs)
1760 & ((HOST_WIDE_INT_1 << BITS_PER_UNIT) - 1);
1761 int shift = BITS_PER_UNIT;
1762 while (shift < HOST_BITS_PER_WIDE_INT)
1763 {
1764 c |= (c << shift);
1765 shift <<= 1;
1766 }
1767 read_reg = gen_int_mode (c, store_mode);
1768 read_reg = extract_low_bits (read_mode, store_mode, read_reg);
1769 }
1770 }
1771 else if (store_info->const_rhs
1772 && (require_cst
1773 || GET_MODE_CLASS (read_mode) != GET_MODE_CLASS (store_mode)))
1774 read_reg = extract_low_bits (read_mode, store_mode,
1775 copy_rtx (store_info->const_rhs));
1776 else
1777 read_reg = extract_low_bits (read_mode, store_mode,
1778 copy_rtx (store_info->rhs));
1779 if (require_cst && read_reg && !CONSTANT_P (read_reg))
1780 read_reg = NULL_RTX;
1781 return read_reg;
1782}
1783
1784/* Take a sequence of:
1785 A <- r1
1786 ...
1787 ... <- A
1788
1789 and change it into
1790 r2 <- r1
1791 A <- r1
1792 ...
1793 ... <- r2
1794
1795 or
1796
1797 r3 <- extract (r1)
1798 r3 <- r3 >> shift
1799 r2 <- extract (r3)
1800 ... <- r2
1801
1802 or
1803
1804 r2 <- extract (r1)
1805 ... <- r2
1806
1807 Depending on the alignment and the mode of the store and
1808 subsequent load.
1809
1810
1811 The STORE_INFO and STORE_INSN are for the store and READ_INFO
1812 and READ_INSN are for the read. Return true if the replacement
1813 went ok. */
1814
1815static bool
1816replace_read (store_info *store_info, insn_info_t store_insn,
1817 read_info_t read_info, insn_info_t read_insn, rtx *loc,
1818 bitmap regs_live)
1819{
1820 machine_mode store_mode = GET_MODE (store_info->mem);
1821 machine_mode read_mode = GET_MODE (read_info->mem);
1822 rtx_insn *insns, *this_insn;
1823 rtx read_reg;
1824 basic_block bb;
1825
1826 if (!dbg_cnt (dse))
1827 return false;
1828
1829 /* Create a sequence of instructions to set up the read register.
1830 This sequence goes immediately before the store and its result
1831 is read by the load.
1832
1833 We need to keep this in perspective. We are replacing a read
1834 with a sequence of insns, but the read will almost certainly be
1835 in cache, so it is not going to be an expensive one. Thus, we
1836 are not willing to do a multi insn shift or worse a subroutine
1837 call to get rid of the read. */
1838 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1839 fprintf (dump_file, "trying to replace %smode load in insn %d"
1840 " from %smode store in insn %d\n",
1841 GET_MODE_NAME (read_mode), INSN_UID (read_insn->insn),
1842 GET_MODE_NAME (store_mode), INSN_UID (store_insn->insn));
1843 start_sequence ();
1844 bb = BLOCK_FOR_INSN (read_insn->insn);
1845 read_reg = get_stored_val (store_info,
1846 read_mode, read_info->begin, read_info->end,
1847 bb, false);
1848 if (read_reg == NULL_RTX)
1849 {
1850 end_sequence ();
1851 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1852 fprintf (dump_file, " -- could not extract bits of stored value\n");
1853 return false;
1854 }
1855 /* Force the value into a new register so that it won't be clobbered
1856 between the store and the load. */
1857 read_reg = copy_to_mode_reg (read_mode, read_reg);
1858 insns = get_insns ();
1859 end_sequence ();
1860
1861 if (insns != NULL_RTX)
1862 {
1863 /* Now we have to scan the set of new instructions to see if the
1864 sequence contains and sets of hardregs that happened to be
1865 live at this point. For instance, this can happen if one of
1866 the insns sets the CC and the CC happened to be live at that
1867 point. This does occasionally happen, see PR 37922. */
1868 bitmap regs_set = BITMAP_ALLOC (&reg_obstack);
1869
1870 for (this_insn = insns; this_insn != NULL_RTX; this_insn = NEXT_INSN (this_insn))
1871 note_stores (PATTERN (this_insn), look_for_hardregs, regs_set);
1872
1873 bitmap_and_into (regs_set, regs_live);
1874 if (!bitmap_empty_p (regs_set))
1875 {
1876 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1877 {
1878 fprintf (dump_file,
1879 "abandoning replacement because sequence clobbers live hardregs:");
1880 df_print_regset (dump_file, regs_set);
1881 }
1882
1883 BITMAP_FREE (regs_set);
1884 return false;
1885 }
1886 BITMAP_FREE (regs_set);
1887 }
1888
1889 if (validate_change (read_insn->insn, loc, read_reg, 0))
1890 {
1891 deferred_change *change = deferred_change_pool.allocate ();
1892
1893 /* Insert this right before the store insn where it will be safe
1894 from later insns that might change it before the read. */
1895 emit_insn_before (insns, store_insn->insn);
1896
1897 /* And now for the kludge part: cselib croaks if you just
1898 return at this point. There are two reasons for this:
1899
1900 1) Cselib has an idea of how many pseudos there are and
1901 that does not include the new ones we just added.
1902
1903 2) Cselib does not know about the move insn we added
1904 above the store_info, and there is no way to tell it
1905 about it, because it has "moved on".
1906
1907 Problem (1) is fixable with a certain amount of engineering.
1908 Problem (2) is requires starting the bb from scratch. This
1909 could be expensive.
1910
1911 So we are just going to have to lie. The move/extraction
1912 insns are not really an issue, cselib did not see them. But
1913 the use of the new pseudo read_insn is a real problem because
1914 cselib has not scanned this insn. The way that we solve this
1915 problem is that we are just going to put the mem back for now
1916 and when we are finished with the block, we undo this. We
1917 keep a table of mems to get rid of. At the end of the basic
1918 block we can put them back. */
1919
1920 *loc = read_info->mem;
1921 change->next = deferred_change_list;
1922 deferred_change_list = change;
1923 change->loc = loc;
1924 change->reg = read_reg;
1925
1926 /* Get rid of the read_info, from the point of view of the
1927 rest of dse, play like this read never happened. */
1928 read_insn->read_rec = read_info->next;
1929 read_info_type_pool.remove (read_info);
1930 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1931 {
1932 fprintf (dump_file, " -- replaced the loaded MEM with ");
1933 print_simple_rtl (dump_file, read_reg);
1934 fprintf (dump_file, "\n");
1935 }
1936 return true;
1937 }
1938 else
1939 {
1940 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1941 {
1942 fprintf (dump_file, " -- replacing the loaded MEM with ");
1943 print_simple_rtl (dump_file, read_reg);
1944 fprintf (dump_file, " led to an invalid instruction\n");
1945 }
1946 return false;
1947 }
1948}
1949
1950/* Check the address of MEM *LOC and kill any appropriate stores that may
1951 be active. */
1952
1953static void
1954check_mem_read_rtx (rtx *loc, bb_info_t bb_info)
1955{
1956 rtx mem = *loc, mem_addr;
1957 insn_info_t insn_info;
1958 HOST_WIDE_INT offset = 0;
1959 HOST_WIDE_INT width = 0;
1960 cselib_val *base = NULL;
1961 int group_id;
1962 read_info_t read_info;
1963
1964 insn_info = bb_info->last_insn;
1965
1966 if ((MEM_ALIAS_SET (mem) == ALIAS_SET_MEMORY_BARRIER)
1967 || (MEM_VOLATILE_P (mem)))
1968 {
1969 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1970 fprintf (dump_file, " adding wild read, volatile or barrier.\n");
1971 add_wild_read (bb_info);
1972 insn_info->cannot_delete = true;
1973 return;
1974 }
1975
1976 /* If it is reading readonly mem, then there can be no conflict with
1977 another write. */
1978 if (MEM_READONLY_P (mem))
1979 return;
1980
1981 if (!canon_address (mem, &group_id, &offset, &base))
1982 {
1983 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
1984 fprintf (dump_file, " adding wild read, canon_address failure.\n");
1985 add_wild_read (bb_info);
1986 return;
1987 }
1988
1989 if (GET_MODE (mem) == BLKmode)
1990 width = -1;
1991 else
1992 width = GET_MODE_SIZE (GET_MODE (mem));
1993
1994 read_info = read_info_type_pool.allocate ();
1995 read_info->group_id = group_id;
1996 read_info->mem = mem;
1997 read_info->begin = offset;
1998 read_info->end = offset + width;
1999 read_info->next = insn_info->read_rec;
2000 insn_info->read_rec = read_info;
2001 if (group_id < 0)
2002 mem_addr = base->val_rtx;
2003 else
2004 {
2005 group_info *group = rtx_group_vec[group_id];
2006 mem_addr = group->canon_base_addr;
2007 }
2008 if (offset)
2009 mem_addr = plus_constant (get_address_mode (mem), mem_addr, offset);
2010
2011 if (group_id >= 0)
2012 {
2013 /* This is the restricted case where the base is a constant or
2014 the frame pointer and offset is a constant. */
2015 insn_info_t i_ptr = active_local_stores;
2016 insn_info_t last = NULL;
2017
2018 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2019 {
2020 if (width == -1)
2021 fprintf (dump_file, " processing const load gid=%d[BLK]\n",
2022 group_id);
2023 else
2024 fprintf (dump_file, " processing const load gid=%d[%d..%d)\n",
2025 group_id, (int)offset, (int)(offset+width));
2026 }
2027
2028 while (i_ptr)
2029 {
2030 bool remove = false;
2031 store_info *store_info = i_ptr->store_rec;
2032
2033 /* Skip the clobbers. */
2034 while (!store_info->is_set)
2035 store_info = store_info->next;
2036
2037 /* There are three cases here. */
2038 if (store_info->group_id < 0)
2039 /* We have a cselib store followed by a read from a
2040 const base. */
2041 remove
2042 = canon_true_dependence (store_info->mem,
2043 GET_MODE (store_info->mem),
2044 store_info->mem_addr,
2045 mem, mem_addr);
2046
2047 else if (group_id == store_info->group_id)
2048 {
2049 /* This is a block mode load. We may get lucky and
2050 canon_true_dependence may save the day. */
2051 if (width == -1)
2052 remove
2053 = canon_true_dependence (store_info->mem,
2054 GET_MODE (store_info->mem),
2055 store_info->mem_addr,
2056 mem, mem_addr);
2057
2058 /* If this read is just reading back something that we just
2059 stored, rewrite the read. */
2060 else
2061 {
2062 if (store_info->rhs
2063 && offset >= store_info->begin
2064 && offset + width <= store_info->end
2065 && all_positions_needed_p (store_info,
2066 offset - store_info->begin,
2067 width)
2068 && replace_read (store_info, i_ptr, read_info,
2069 insn_info, loc, bb_info->regs_live))
2070 return;
2071
2072 /* The bases are the same, just see if the offsets
2073 overlap. */
2074 if ((offset < store_info->end)
2075 && (offset + width > store_info->begin))
2076 remove = true;
2077 }
2078 }
2079
2080 /* else
2081 The else case that is missing here is that the
2082 bases are constant but different. There is nothing
2083 to do here because there is no overlap. */
2084
2085 if (remove)
2086 {
2087 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2088 dump_insn_info ("removing from active", i_ptr);
2089
2090 active_local_stores_len--;
2091 if (last)
2092 last->next_local_store = i_ptr->next_local_store;
2093 else
2094 active_local_stores = i_ptr->next_local_store;
2095 }
2096 else
2097 last = i_ptr;
2098 i_ptr = i_ptr->next_local_store;
2099 }
2100 }
2101 else
2102 {
2103 insn_info_t i_ptr = active_local_stores;
2104 insn_info_t last = NULL;
2105 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2106 {
2107 fprintf (dump_file, " processing cselib load mem:");
2108 print_inline_rtx (dump_file, mem, 0);
2109 fprintf (dump_file, "\n");
2110 }
2111
2112 while (i_ptr)
2113 {
2114 bool remove = false;
2115 store_info *store_info = i_ptr->store_rec;
2116
2117 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2118 fprintf (dump_file, " processing cselib load against insn %d\n",
2119 INSN_UID (i_ptr->insn));
2120
2121 /* Skip the clobbers. */
2122 while (!store_info->is_set)
2123 store_info = store_info->next;
2124
2125 /* If this read is just reading back something that we just
2126 stored, rewrite the read. */
2127 if (store_info->rhs
2128 && store_info->group_id == -1
2129 && store_info->cse_base == base
2130 && width != -1
2131 && offset >= store_info->begin
2132 && offset + width <= store_info->end
2133 && all_positions_needed_p (store_info,
2134 offset - store_info->begin, width)
2135 && replace_read (store_info, i_ptr, read_info, insn_info, loc,
2136 bb_info->regs_live))
2137 return;
2138
2139 remove = canon_true_dependence (store_info->mem,
2140 GET_MODE (store_info->mem),
2141 store_info->mem_addr,
2142 mem, mem_addr);
2143
2144 if (remove)
2145 {
2146 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2147 dump_insn_info ("removing from active", i_ptr);
2148
2149 active_local_stores_len--;
2150 if (last)
2151 last->next_local_store = i_ptr->next_local_store;
2152 else
2153 active_local_stores = i_ptr->next_local_store;
2154 }
2155 else
2156 last = i_ptr;
2157 i_ptr = i_ptr->next_local_store;
2158 }
2159 }
2160}

2179/* Get arguments passed to CALL_INSN. Return TRUE if successful.
2180 So far it only handles arguments passed in registers. */
2181
2182static bool
2183get_call_args (rtx call_insn, tree fn, rtx *args, int nargs)
2184{
2185 CUMULATIVE_ARGS args_so_far_v;
2186 cumulative_args_t args_so_far;
2187 tree arg;
2188 int idx;
2189
2190 INIT_CUMULATIVE_ARGS (args_so_far_v, TREE_TYPE (fn), NULL_RTX, 0, 3);
2191 args_so_far = pack_cumulative_args (&args_so_far_v);
2192
2193 arg = TYPE_ARG_TYPES (TREE_TYPE (fn));
2194 for (idx = 0;
2195 arg != void_list_node && idx < nargs;
2196 arg = TREE_CHAIN (arg), idx++)
2197 {
2198 machine_mode mode = TYPE_MODE (TREE_VALUE (arg));
2199 rtx reg, link, tmp;
2200 reg = targetm.calls.function_arg (args_so_far, mode, NULL_TREE, true);
2201 if (!reg || !REG_P (reg) || GET_MODE (reg) != mode
2202 || GET_MODE_CLASS (mode) != MODE_INT)
2203 return false;
2204
2205 for (link = CALL_INSN_FUNCTION_USAGE (call_insn);
2206 link;
2207 link = XEXP (link, 1))
2208 if (GET_CODE (XEXP (link, 0)) == USE)
2209 {
2210 args[idx] = XEXP (XEXP (link, 0), 0);
2211 if (REG_P (args[idx])
2212 && REGNO (args[idx]) == REGNO (reg)
2213 && (GET_MODE (args[idx]) == mode
2214 || (GET_MODE_CLASS (GET_MODE (args[idx])) == MODE_INT
2215 && (GET_MODE_SIZE (GET_MODE (args[idx]))
2216 <= UNITS_PER_WORD)
2217 && (GET_MODE_SIZE (GET_MODE (args[idx]))
2218 > GET_MODE_SIZE (mode)))))
2219 break;
2220 }
2221 if (!link)
2222 return false;
2223
2224 tmp = cselib_expand_value_rtx (args[idx], scratch, 5);
2225 if (GET_MODE (args[idx]) != mode)
2226 {
2227 if (!tmp || !CONST_INT_P (tmp))
2228 return false;
2229 tmp = gen_int_mode (INTVAL (tmp), mode);
2230 }
2231 if (tmp)
2232 args[idx] = tmp;
2233
2234 targetm.calls.function_arg_advance (args_so_far, mode, NULL_TREE, true);
2235 }
2236 if (arg != void_list_node || idx != nargs)
2237 return false;
2238 return true;
2239}

2253/* Apply record_store to all candidate stores in INSN. Mark INSN
2254 if some part of it is not a candidate store and assigns to a
2255 non-register target. */
2256
2257static void
2258scan_insn (bb_info_t bb_info, rtx_insn *insn)
2259{
2260 rtx body;
2261 insn_info_type *insn_info = insn_info_type_pool.allocate ();
2262 int mems_found = 0;
2263 memset (insn_info, 0, sizeof (struct insn_info_type));
2264
2265 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2266 fprintf (dump_file, "\n**scanning insn=%d\n",
2267 INSN_UID (insn));
2268
2269 insn_info->prev_insn = bb_info->last_insn;
2270 insn_info->insn = insn;
2271 bb_info->last_insn = insn_info;
2272
2273 if (DEBUG_INSN_P (insn))
2274 {
2275 insn_info->cannot_delete = true;
2276 return;
2277 }
2278
2279 /* Look at all of the uses in the insn. */
2280 note_uses (&PATTERN (insn), check_mem_read_use, bb_info);
2281
2282 if (CALL_P (insn))
2283 {
2284 bool const_call;
2285 rtx call, sym;
2286 tree memset_call = NULL_TREE;
2287
2288 insn_info->cannot_delete = true;
2289
2290 /* Const functions cannot do anything bad i.e. read memory,
2291 however, they can read their parameters which may have
2292 been pushed onto the stack.
2293 memset and bzero don't read memory either. */
2294 const_call = RTL_CONST_CALL_P (insn);
2295 if (!const_call
2296 && (call = get_call_rtx_from (insn))
2297 && (sym = XEXP (XEXP (call, 0), 0))
2298 && GET_CODE (sym) == SYMBOL_REF
2299 && SYMBOL_REF_DECL (sym)
2300 && TREE_CODE (SYMBOL_REF_DECL (sym)) == FUNCTION_DECL
2301 && DECL_BUILT_IN_CLASS (SYMBOL_REF_DECL (sym)) == BUILT_IN_NORMAL
2302 && DECL_FUNCTION_CODE (SYMBOL_REF_DECL (sym)) == BUILT_IN_MEMSET)
2303 memset_call = SYMBOL_REF_DECL (sym);
2304
2305 if (const_call || memset_call)
2306 {
2307 insn_info_t i_ptr = active_local_stores;
2308 insn_info_t last = NULL;
2309
2310 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2311 fprintf (dump_file, "%s call %d\n",
2312 const_call ? "const" : "memset", INSN_UID (insn));
2313
2314 /* See the head comment of the frame_read field. */
2315 if (reload_completed
2316 /* Tail calls are storing their arguments using
2317 arg pointer. If it is a frame pointer on the target,
2318 even before reload we need to kill frame pointer based
2319 stores. */
2320 || (SIBLING_CALL_P (insn)
2321 && HARD_FRAME_POINTER_IS_ARG_POINTER))
2322 insn_info->frame_read = true;
2323
2324 /* Loop over the active stores and remove those which are
2325 killed by the const function call. */
2326 while (i_ptr)
2327 {
2328 bool remove_store = false;
2329
2330 /* The stack pointer based stores are always killed. */
2331 if (i_ptr->stack_pointer_based)
2332 remove_store = true;
2333
2334 /* If the frame is read, the frame related stores are killed. */
2335 else if (insn_info->frame_read)
2336 {
2337 store_info *store_info = i_ptr->store_rec;
2338
2339 /* Skip the clobbers. */
2340 while (!store_info->is_set)
2341 store_info = store_info->next;
2342
2343 if (store_info->group_id >= 0
2344 && rtx_group_vec[store_info->group_id]->frame_related)
2345 remove_store = true;
2346 }
2347
2348 if (remove_store)
2349 {
2350 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2351 dump_insn_info ("removing from active", i_ptr);
2352
2353 active_local_stores_len--;
2354 if (last)
2355 last->next_local_store = i_ptr->next_local_store;
2356 else
2357 active_local_stores = i_ptr->next_local_store;
2358 }
2359 else
2360 last = i_ptr;
2361
2362 i_ptr = i_ptr->next_local_store;
2363 }
2364
2365 if (memset_call)
2366 {
2367 rtx args[3];
2368 if (get_call_args (insn, memset_call, args, 3)
2369 && CONST_INT_P (args[1])
2370 && CONST_INT_P (args[2])
2371 && INTVAL (args[2]) > 0)
2372 {
2373 rtx mem = gen_rtx_MEM (BLKmode, args[0]);
2374 set_mem_size (mem, INTVAL (args[2]));
2375 body = gen_rtx_SET (mem, args[1]);
2376 mems_found += record_store (body, bb_info);
2377 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2378 fprintf (dump_file, "handling memset as BLKmode store\n");
2379 if (mems_found == 1)
2380 {
2381 if (active_local_stores_len++
2382 >= PARAM_VALUE (PARAM_MAX_DSE_ACTIVE_LOCAL_STORES))
2383 {
2384 active_local_stores_len = 1;
2385 active_local_stores = NULL;
2386 }
2387 insn_info->fixed_regs_live
2388 = copy_fixed_regs (bb_info->regs_live);
2389 insn_info->next_local_store = active_local_stores;
2390 active_local_stores = insn_info;
2391 }
2392 }
2393 else
2394 clear_rhs_from_active_local_stores ();
2395 }
2396 }
2397 else if (SIBLING_CALL_P (insn) && reload_completed)
2398 /* Arguments for a sibling call that are pushed to memory are passed
2399 using the incoming argument pointer of the current function. After
2400 reload that might be (and likely is) frame pointer based. */
2401 add_wild_read (bb_info);
2402 else
2403 /* Every other call, including pure functions, may read any memory
2404 that is not relative to the frame. */
2405 add_non_frame_wild_read (bb_info);
2406
2407 return;
2408 }
2409
2410 /* Assuming that there are sets in these insns, we cannot delete
2411 them. */
2412 if ((GET_CODE (PATTERN (insn)) == CLOBBER)
2413 || volatile_refs_p (PATTERN (insn))
2414 || (!cfun->can_delete_dead_exceptions && !insn_nothrow_p (insn))
2415 || (RTX_FRAME_RELATED_P (insn))
2416 || find_reg_note (insn, REG_FRAME_RELATED_EXPR, NULL_RTX))
2417 insn_info->cannot_delete = true;
2418
2419 body = PATTERN (insn);
2420 if (GET_CODE (body) == PARALLEL)
2421 {
2422 int i;
2423 for (i = 0; i < XVECLEN (body, 0); i++)
2424 mems_found += record_store (XVECEXP (body, 0, i), bb_info);
2425 }
2426 else
2427 mems_found += record_store (body, bb_info);
2428
2429 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2430 fprintf (dump_file, "mems_found = %d, cannot_delete = %s\n",
2431 mems_found, insn_info->cannot_delete ? "true" : "false");
2432
2433 /* If we found some sets of mems, add it into the active_local_stores so
2434 that it can be locally deleted if found dead or used for
2435 replace_read and redundant constant store elimination. Otherwise mark
2436 it as cannot delete. This simplifies the processing later. */
2437 if (mems_found == 1)
2438 {
2439 if (active_local_stores_len++
2440 >= PARAM_VALUE (PARAM_MAX_DSE_ACTIVE_LOCAL_STORES))
2441 {
2442 active_local_stores_len = 1;
2443 active_local_stores = NULL;
2444 }
2445 insn_info->fixed_regs_live = copy_fixed_regs (bb_info->regs_live);
2446 insn_info->next_local_store = active_local_stores;
2447 active_local_stores = insn_info;
2448 }
2449 else
2450 insn_info->cannot_delete = true;
2451}

2454/* Remove BASE from the set of active_local_stores. This is a
2455 callback from cselib that is used to get rid of the stores in
2456 active_local_stores. */
2457
2458static void
2459remove_useless_values (cselib_val *base)
2460{
2461 insn_info_t insn_info = active_local_stores;
2462 insn_info_t last = NULL;
2463
2464 while (insn_info)
2465 {
2466 store_info *store_info = insn_info->store_rec;
2467 bool del = false;
2468
2469 /* If ANY of the store_infos match the cselib group that is
2470 being deleted, then the insn can not be deleted. */
2471 while (store_info)
2472 {
2473 if ((store_info->group_id == -1)
2474 && (store_info->cse_base == base))
2475 {
2476 del = true;
2477 break;
2478 }
2479 store_info = store_info->next;
2480 }
2481
2482 if (del)
2483 {
2484 active_local_stores_len--;
2485 if (last)
2486 last->next_local_store = insn_info->next_local_store;
2487 else
2488 active_local_stores = insn_info->next_local_store;
2489 free_store_info (insn_info);
2490 }
2491 else
2492 last = insn_info;
2493
2494 insn_info = insn_info->next_local_store;
2495 }
2496}

2499/* Do all of step 1. */
2500
2501static void
2502dse_step1 (void)
2503{
2504 basic_block bb;
2505 bitmap regs_live = BITMAP_ALLOC (&reg_obstack);
2506
2507 cselib_init (0);
2508 all_blocks = BITMAP_ALLOC (NULL);
2509 bitmap_set_bit (all_blocks, ENTRY_BLOCK);
2510 bitmap_set_bit (all_blocks, EXIT_BLOCK);
2511
2512 FOR_ALL_BB_FN (bb, cfun)
2513 {
2514 insn_info_t ptr;
2515 bb_info_t bb_info = dse_bb_info_type_pool.allocate ();
2516
2517 memset (bb_info, 0, sizeof (dse_bb_info_type));
2518 bitmap_set_bit (all_blocks, bb->index);
2519 bb_info->regs_live = regs_live;
2520
2521 bitmap_copy (regs_live, DF_LR_IN (bb));
2522 df_simulate_initialize_forwards (bb, regs_live);
2523
2524 bb_table[bb->index] = bb_info;
2525 cselib_discard_hook = remove_useless_values;
2526
2527 if (bb->index >= NUM_FIXED_BLOCKS)
2528 {
2529 rtx_insn *insn;
2530
2531 active_local_stores = NULL;
2532 active_local_stores_len = 0;
2533 cselib_clear_table ();
2534
2535 /* Scan the insns. */
2536 FOR_BB_INSNS (bb, insn)
2537 {
2538 if (INSN_P (insn))
2539 scan_insn (bb_info, insn);
2540 cselib_process_insn (insn);
2541 if (INSN_P (insn))
2542 df_simulate_one_insn_forwards (bb, insn, regs_live);
2543 }
2544
2545 /* This is something of a hack, because the global algorithm
2546 is supposed to take care of the case where stores go dead
2547 at the end of the function. However, the global
2548 algorithm must take a more conservative view of block
2549 mode reads than the local alg does. So to get the case
2550 where you have a store to the frame followed by a non
2551 overlapping block more read, we look at the active local
2552 stores at the end of the function and delete all of the
2553 frame and spill based ones. */
2554 if (stores_off_frame_dead_at_return
2555 && (EDGE_COUNT (bb->succs) == 0
2556 || (single_succ_p (bb)
2557 && single_succ (bb) == EXIT_BLOCK_PTR_FOR_FN (cfun)
2558 && ! crtl->calls_eh_return)))
2559 {
2560 insn_info_t i_ptr = active_local_stores;
2561 while (i_ptr)
2562 {
2563 store_info *store_info = i_ptr->store_rec;
2564
2565 /* Skip the clobbers. */
2566 while (!store_info->is_set)
2567 store_info = store_info->next;
2568 if (store_info->group_id >= 0)
2569 {
2570 group_info *group = rtx_group_vec[store_info->group_id];
2571 if (group->frame_related && !i_ptr->cannot_delete)
2572 delete_dead_store_insn (i_ptr);
2573 }
2574
2575 i_ptr = i_ptr->next_local_store;
2576 }
2577 }
2578
2579 /* Get rid of the loads that were discovered in
2580 replace_read. Cselib is finished with this block. */
2581 while (deferred_change_list)
2582 {
2583 deferred_change *next = deferred_change_list->next;
2584
2585 /* There is no reason to validate this change. That was
2586 done earlier. */
2587 *deferred_change_list->loc = deferred_change_list->reg;
2588 deferred_change_pool.remove (deferred_change_list);
2589 deferred_change_list = next;
2590 }
2591
2592 /* Get rid of all of the cselib based store_infos in this
2593 block and mark the containing insns as not being
2594 deletable. */
2595 ptr = bb_info->last_insn;
2596 while (ptr)
2597 {
2598 if (ptr->contains_cselib_groups)
2599 {
2600 store_info *s_info = ptr->store_rec;
2601 while (s_info && !s_info->is_set)
2602 s_info = s_info->next;
2603 if (s_info
2604 && s_info->redundant_reason
2605 && s_info->redundant_reason->insn
2606 && !ptr->cannot_delete)
2607 {
2608 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2609 fprintf (dump_file, "Locally deleting insn %d "
2610 "because insn %d stores the "
2611 "same value and couldn't be "
2612 "eliminated\n",
2613 INSN_UID (ptr->insn),
2614 INSN_UID (s_info->redundant_reason->insn));
2615 delete_dead_store_insn (ptr);
2616 }
2617 free_store_info (ptr);
2618 }
2619 else
2620 {
2621 store_info *s_info;
2622
2623 /* Free at least positions_needed bitmaps. */
2624 for (s_info = ptr->store_rec; s_info; s_info = s_info->next)
2625 if (s_info->is_large)
2626 {
2627 BITMAP_FREE (s_info->positions_needed.large.bmap);
2628 s_info->is_large = false;
2629 }
2630 }
2631 ptr = ptr->prev_insn;
2632 }
2633
2634 cse_store_info_pool.release ();
2635 }
2636 bb_info->regs_live = NULL;
2637 }
2638
2639 BITMAP_FREE (regs_live);
2640 cselib_finish ();
2641 rtx_group_table->empty ();
2642}

2645/*----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2646 Second step.
2647
2648 Assign each byte position in the stores that we are going to
2649 analyze globally to a position in the bitmaps. Returns true if
2650 there are any bit positions assigned.
2651----------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
2652
2653static void
2654dse_step2_init (void)
2655{
2656 unsigned int i;
2657 group_info *group;
2658
2659 FOR_EACH_VEC_ELT (rtx_group_vec, i, group)
2660 {
2661 /* For all non stack related bases, we only consider a store to
2662 be deletable if there are two or more stores for that
2663 position. This is because it takes one store to make the
2664 other store redundant. However, for the stores that are
2665 stack related, we consider them if there is only one store
2666 for the position. We do this because the stack related
2667 stores can be deleted if their is no read between them and
2668 the end of the function.
2669
2670 To make this work in the current framework, we take the stack
2671 related bases add all of the bits from store1 into store2.
2672 This has the effect of making the eligible even if there is
2673 only one store. */
2674
2675 if (stores_off_frame_dead_at_return && group->frame_related)
2676 {
2677 bitmap_ior_into (group->store2_n, group->store1_n);
2678 bitmap_ior_into (group->store2_p, group->store1_p);
2679 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2680 fprintf (dump_file, "group %d is frame related ", i);
2681 }
2682
2683 group->offset_map_size_n++;
2684 group->offset_map_n = XOBNEWVEC (&dse_obstack, int,
2685 group->offset_map_size_n);
2686 group->offset_map_size_p++;
2687 group->offset_map_p = XOBNEWVEC (&dse_obstack, int,
2688 group->offset_map_size_p);
2689 group->process_globally = false;
2690 if (dump_file && (dump_flags & TDF_DETAILS))
2691 {
2692 fprintf (dump_file, "group %d(%d+%d): ", i,
2693 (int)bitmap_count_bits (group->store2_n),
2694 (int)bitmap_count_bits (group->store2_p));
2695 bitmap_print (dump_file, group->store2_n, "n ", " ");
2696 bitmap_print (dump_file, group->store2_p, "p ", "\n");
2697 }
2698 }
2699}

2702/* Init the offset tables. */
2703
2704static bool
2705dse_step2 (void)
2706{
2707 unsigned int i;
2708 group_info *group;
2709 /* Position 0 is unused because 0 is used in the maps to mean
2710 unused. */
2711 current_position = 1;
2712 FOR_EACH_VEC_ELT (rtx_group_vec, i, group)
2713 {
2714 bitmap_iterator bi;
2715 unsigned int j;
2716
2717 memset (group->offset_map_n, 0, sizeof (int) * group->offset_map_size_n);
2718 memset (group->offset_map_p, 0, sizeof (int) * group->offset_map_size_p);
2719 bitmap_clear (group->group_kill);
2720
2721 EXECUTE_IF_SET_IN_BITMAP (group->store2_n, 0, j, bi)
2722 {
2723 bitmap_set_bit (group->group_kill, current_position);
2724 if (bitmap_bit_p (group->escaped_n, j))
2725 bitmap_set_bit (kill_on_calls, current_position);
2726 group->offset_map_n[j] = current_position++;
2727 group->process_globally = true;
2728 }
2729 EXECUTE_IF_SET_IN_BITMAP (group->store2_p, 0, j, bi)
2730 {
2731 bitmap_set_bit (group->group_kill, current_position);
2732 if (bitmap_bit_p (group->escaped_p, j))
2733 bitmap_set_bit (kill_on_calls, current_position);
2734 group->offset_map_p[j] = current_position++;
2735 group->process_globally = true;
2736 }
2737 }
2738 return current_position != 1;
2739}

2750/* Look up the bitmap index for OFFSET in GROUP_INFO. If it is not
2751 there, return 0. */
2752
2753static int
2754get_bitmap_index (group_info *group_info, HOST_WIDE_INT offset)
2755{
2756 if (offset < 0)
2757 {
2758 HOST_WIDE_INT offset_p = -offset;
2759 if (offset_p >= group_info->offset_map_size_n)
2760 return 0;
2761 return group_info->offset_map_n[offset_p];
2762 }
2763 else
2764 {
2765 if (offset >= group_info->offset_map_size_p)
2766 return 0;
2767 return group_info->offset_map_p[offset];
2768 }
2769}
